Title: Blandings Castle and Elsewhere
Comments: six Blandings, five Mulliner, and one about Bobbie Wickham which does not fit into any of the series

Title: Bring on the Girls!
Description: An autobiographical collaboration with Guy Bolton, subtitled "The Improbable Story of Our Life in Musical Comedy, With Pictures To Prove It".

Title: Carry on, Jeeves
Description: Ten short stories, five repeated in some form from My Man Jeeves

Title: Eggs, Beans and Crumpets
Comments: Four short stories about Bingo Little and one about Freddie Fitch-Fitch in a book of nine

Title: Lord Emsworth Acts for the Best
Louder and Funnier
Description: A collection of articles originally written for Vanity Fair magazine

Title: Much Obliged, Jeeves
Comments: In which appears the only mention of Jeeves's Christian name, Reginald
USTitle: Jeeves and the Tie That Binds

Title: My Man Jeeves
Description: Eight short stories, four about Jeeves and four about Reggie Pepper

Title: Nothing Serious
Comments: One Bingo Little and one Conky Biddle in a book of ten

Title: Performing Flea
Description: Subtitled "A Self-Portrait in Letters by P.G.Wodehouse, With an Introduction and Additional Notes by W. Townend"

Title: Piccadilly Jim
Comments: Partially a sequel to The Little Nugget

Title: Plum Pie
Comments: one about Jeeves, one golf, one Freddie Threepwood, two Bingo Little, one Ukridge, two Freddie Widgeon, and one Mr Mulliner

Title: Ring for Jeeves
Comments: In which Bill Belfry "borrows" Jeeves from Bertie (U. S. title: The Return of Jeeves)

Title: The Coming of Bill
Comments: First serialised 1914 as The Great White Hope

Title: The Globe By the Way Book
Description: A compilation from the column "By the Way", written by Wodehouse and Herbert Westbrook, which appeared in The Globe

Title: The Inimitable Jeeves
Description: A collection of eleven short stories related to each other (U.S. title: Jeeves)

Title: The Man with Two Left Feet
Comments: A collection of thirteen short stories, one of which, "Extricating Young Gussie", introduces Jeeves, Bertie, and Aunt Agatha, though Bertie's surname may be Mannering-Phipps rather than Wooster. Bertie has a cousin named Gussie Mannering-Phipps. Bertram did not have a surname, and it remains a matter of considerable debate amongst Wodehouse scholars as to whether he was indeed Bertie Wooster, or merely Bertie Mannering-Phipps.

Title: Young Men in Spats
Description: Eleven short stories about members of The Drones Club
Comments: One story ("Uncle Fred Flits By") introduces Uncle Fred
